Creating a simple A-Frame VR scene that mimics the style of a Commander Keen clone can be done using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript all embedded in a single file. Below is an example of such a web app. This example includes a basic environment, a player character, and some interactive elements.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Commander Keen Clone in A-Frame</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; }
        #instructions {
            position: absolute;
            top: 20px;
            left: 20px;
            color: white;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            z-index: 10;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="instructions">
        <h2>Commander Keen Clone</h2>
        <p>Use WASD to move, and space to jump!</p>
    </div>
    <a-scene>
        <a-sky color="#87CEEB"></a-sky>

        <a-box position="-1 0.5 -3" rotation="0 45 0" color="#4CC3D9"></a-box>
        <a-sphere position="1 1 -5" radius="1.25" color="#EF2D5E"></a-sphere>
        <a-cylinder position="0 0 -5" radius="0.5" height="1.5" color="#FFC65D"></a-cylinder>

        <a-entity id="player" position="0 1.6 0" camera look-controls>
            <a-entity geometry="primitive: box" material="color: #FF0000" position="0 0 -1" scale="0.5 1 0.5"></a-entity>
        </a-entity>

        <a-entity position="0 0 -10" rotation="0 0 0" text="value: Welcome to the Commander Keen Clone; color: #FFFFFF; align: center;"></a-entity>

        <a-entity light="type: directional; color: #FFFFFF" position="1 4 1"></a-entity>
    </a-scene>

    <script>
        // Player movement controls
        const player = document.getElementById('player');
        const speed = 0.1;

        document.addEventListener('keydown', (event) => {
            switch (event.key) {
                case 'w':
                    player.object3D.position.z -= speed;
                    break;
                case 's':
                    player.object3D.position.z += speed;
                    break;
                case 'a':
                    player.object3D.position.x -= speed;
                    break;
                case 'd':
                    player.object3D.position.x += speed;
                    break;
                case ' ':
                    player.object3D.position.y += 1; // Simple jump
                    setTimeout(() => {
                        player.object3D.position.y -= 1; // Return to ground
                    }, 300);
                    break;
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **A-Frame Library**: The A-Frame library is included via a CDN link.
- **Scene Setup**: The `<a-scene>` element contains various 3D objects (box, sphere, cylinder) to represent the environment.
- **Player Entity**: A simple player entity is created with a box representing the character.
- **Movement Controls**: Basic movement controls are implemented using the keyboard (WASD for movement and space for jumping).
- **Instructions**: A simple overlay with instructions is provided for the user.

### How to Use:
1. Copy the code above into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `commander_keen_clone.html`).
3. Open the file in a web browser that supports WebVR (like Chrome or Firefox).
4. Use the WASD keys to move and the spacebar to jump.

This is a very basic implementation and can be expanded with more features, textures, and interactions to create a more complete game experience.
